'dzam bu'i gling|“Rose Apple Island,” this was the name commonly used for one of the four great continents of ancient Buddhist cosmology, generally understood to refer to the Indian subcontinent.
'dzam bu'i gling|The continent on which we live, according to ancient South-Asian cosmology. It is the southernmost of the four continents surrounding Mount Sumeru, the mountain at the center of our world system. It is shaped like a jambū fruit.
