drang srong smra ba|“Speech of the Sages,” an alternate name for Ṛṣipatana ({drang srong lhung ba}), the location of the Deer Park outside of Vārāṇasī where the Buddha first turned the wheel of Dharma.
drang srong smra ba|A place in the Deer Park (Mṛgadāva) outside Vārāṇasī where the Buddha Śākyamuni first turned the wheel of Dharma. The name, meaning “speech of ṛṣis (sages or seers),” may refer to a story that in this same place during the time of the previous Buddha, Kāśyapa, five hundred seers (in some versions pratyekabuddhas) uttered prophecies and attained nirvāṇa on hearing that the Buddha Śākyamuni was to come. Also known as Ṛṣipatana.
