khrel yod bzang po|Buddha in the presence of whom the buddha Netra (470 according to the third enumeration) first gave rise to the mind of awakening.
khrel yod|A mental state that induces one to avoid immoral behavior out of concern for what others will think or say about oneself if one misbehaves.
khrel|One of the eleven virtuous mental factors (Tib. {sems byung dge ba}; Skt. kuśalacaitta), a subgroup of the mental states or factors associated with the mind (Skt. caitasika, caitta), according to the Abhidharma. According to Vasubandhu (in his Pañcaskandhaka), {khrel} (“embarrassment” or “shame”) is different from {ngo tsha} (“scruples,” “conscience”) in that it is independent from others’ judgment of one’s behavior, and solely internal, in that it contradicts one’s internalized values. See “guilty conscience.”
