kun tu bzang po'i spyod pa'i smon lam|The Samanta bhadra caryā praṇidhāna appears in the final part of the Gaṇḍa vyūha sūtra, which itself forms part of the Buddhāvataṃsaka sūtra. It is well-known in Tibet, where it has been the subject of numerous commentaries. It continues to be recited daily in some monastic traditions in Tibet and China. The work also goes under the Sanskrit titles Bhadracari(-ī), and Bhadra caryā praṇidhāna. See Skilling and Saerji 2013, 198 n. 30.
