ngan pa|Lacking knowledge of or being ignorant [of the Dharma]. J. S. Negi (Negi 935, s.v. {ngan pa}) cites a few instances where Tibetan {ngan pa} represents the Sanskrit semantic field “lack of understanding,” e.g., Bodhi caryāvatāra (Tib. {ngan pa}; Skt. ajñaḥ “not knowing,” “devoid of knowledge,” “stupid,” “foolish,” etc.); Jātakamālā (Tib. {ngan pa}; Skt. jaḍā matiḥ “dull,” “stupid,” “irrational”); Avadāna kalpalatā (Tib. {ngan pa}; Skt. mūrkhāḥ “stupid, dull-headed; a fool”). Context suggests that this is one sense of {ngan pa} in Exposition of Karma when it talks about the Dharma and knowledge thereof. Also translated here as “bad deed.”\nSee also https://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-072-039.html#UT22084-072-039-88 .
