seng ge|In The Hundred Deeds, a certain army chief in Vaiśālī by this name appears twice (in part 4: “ https://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-073-001.html#UT22084-073-001-2238 ” and in part 5: “ https://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-073-001.html#UT22084-073-001-2604 ”). It is not clear whether this army chief refers the same person or not.\nIn the first story, he is the father of a ugly and stinking son who heard the Dharma from the Blessed One, went forth, and was healed of his afflictions. In the second story, he is the father of Good Compassion who was sentenced to death but was released and went forth under the Buddha.
