tshangs pa gtsug phud can|In some canonical sources, this name denotes Brahmā Sahāmpati, the lord of the Sahā universe who famously asked the Buddha Śākyamuni to teach for the first time. See, for example, https://read.84000.co/translation/toh47.html (Toh 47), https://read.84000.co/translation/toh95.html (Toh 95), and https://read.84000.co/translation/toh147.html (Toh 147). But in another canonical text, https://read.84000.co/translation/toh113.html (Toh 113), it is used for a different Brahmā god. The current sūtra does not provide enough context to allow us to determine which of these two gods is under discussion.
